<paragraph blockId="17.[160,1155,1389,1554]" box="[160,409,1389,1415]" pageId="17" pageNumber="282">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,409,1389,1415]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="282">External morphology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[160,1155,1389,1554]" pageId="17" pageNumber="282">Body flat, laterally compressed, ending in a fishtail shape; translucent tegument, internal organs seen by transparency (four digestive gland ramifications, reproductive and nervous systems); numerous yellow, iridescent spots on dorsal and ventral sides. Rhinophores long, smooth, slightly rippled once in ethanol.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="17" pageNumber="282" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="17.[160,1155,1598,1693]" box="[160,252,1598,1624]" pageId="17" pageNumber="282">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[160,252,1598,1624]" italics="true" pageId="17" pageNumber="282">Ecology</emphasis>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="17.[160,1155,1598,1693]" pageId="17" pageNumber="282">The species lives in the open sea, generally at great depths, having a body adapted for swimming. Feeds on jellyfish, although its diet is not well studied.</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
